<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-185-079 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 532 656</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 1 1991 v13 n13 p5(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big Blue reneges on plan to sell XGA chips: intends to license XGAtechnology instead. (IBM's extended graphics array technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Krohn, Nico.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM decides not to sell XGA chips, but instead chooses to licensethe graphics board technology to chip manufacturers.andP;  The decisionsurprises graphics board manufacturers who believed that theywould be supplied with the XGA chips by IBM.andP;  The decision isexpected to delay offerings of low-cost XGA graphics boards thatwould compete with IBM's $1,095 XGA boards for PS/2microcomputers.andP;  IBM expects cash or patent rights from companieslicensing the technology.andP;  XGA licensees stand to gain as much asa 15-month lead on companies that do not get licenses and attemptto develop their own versions.andP;  Clones may not appear on themarket as soon as they might otherwise have had if IBMmanufactured the chip, but it is expected that XGA will become anindustry standard anyway because of IBM's licensing plans.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Licenses).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Graphics CoprocessorsIntegrated CircuitsLicensingStrategic PlanningMarketing StrategyGraphics Boards/Cards.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>